# Real‑world Navigation

Most apps combine multiple navigators: a bottom tab bar, with each tab having its own stack.

You can nest navigators just like any component:

```jsx
function HomeStack() {
  return (
    <Stack.Navigator>
      <Stack.Screen name="Home" component={Home} />
      <Stack.Screen name="Details" component={Details} />
    </Stack.Navigator>
  );
}

function SettingsStack() {
  return (
    <Stack.Navigator>
      <Stack.Screen name="Settings" component={Settings} />
      <Stack.Screen name="Profile" component={Profile} />
    </Stack.Navigator>
  );
}

// In the root
<Tab.Navigator>
  <Tab.Screen name="HomeTab" component={HomeStack} />
  <Tab.Screen name="SettingsTab" component={SettingsStack} />
</Tab.Navigator>
```

## When is a Screen Focused?

In a stack, screens are not unmounted when you go back; they stay mounted. In tabs, screens are mounted when first visited and stay mounted.

To know when a screen comes into focus (e.g., to refresh data), use the `useFocusEffect` hook or the `useIsFocused` hook.

```jsx
import { useFocusEffect } from '@react-navigation/native';

useFocusEffect(
  React.useCallback(() => {
    // Do something when screen is focused
    return () => {
      // Do something when screen is unfocused (cleanup)
    };
  }, [])
);
```

You can conditionally render based on focus:

```jsx
import { useIsFocused } from '@react-navigation/native';

function MyScreen() {
  const isFocused = useIsFocused();

  return (
    <View>
      {isFocused ? <Text>Screen is focused</Text> : <Text>Not focused</Text>}
    </View>
  );
}
```

This is useful for starting/stopping animations or live data.
